<DOC><DOCNO> AP880317-0124 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-17-88 1245EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--BusStrike     03-17 0193</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Bus Strike,0199</SECOND><HEAD>Public Buses Off City Streets</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bus workers began an indefinite strikefor more pay on Thursday, forcing the capital's 5 million commutersto find alternate transportation.   More than 550 employees of the Delhi Transport Corp. werearrested under the Essential Services Maintenance Act, whichprohibits employees of essential services such as police, hospitalsand the fire brigade from going on strike, said police spokesmanRavi Pawar.   The strike, which idled the city's 5,000 passenger buses, forcedmany people to walk or cycle to work.   A lucky few managed to engage three-wheeled scooter rickshawsand taxis, which increased fares because of the strike. Someprivate buses transported commuters for a flat rate of about 16cents, double the normal city service fare.   School examinations scheduled for Thursday were postponedbecause of the strike.   In Parliament, Transport Minister Rajesh Pilot said the strikewas illegal and said the government would take action against theworkers.   Buses are the main form of transport in New Delhi, a city of 8million people. A rail system is used by few people because of itslimited area of operation.</TEXT></DOC>